  <li id="comment-300" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2004/08/slow-roasting/#comment-300"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2007-05-22T15:57:00-04:00">Tuesday, May 22, 2007 at 3:57 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Not to worry, dc365.  You can use your nonfat yogurt.  I&#8217;ve used nonfat before, and it works fine &#8211; it&#8217;s just that the cake will be a teensy bit drier and more crumbly.  As for when to glaze it, you can go either way.  I might suggest, though, that you glaze it the day you plan to serve it, just so that the glaze doesn&#8217;t get smudged or mussed when the cake is wrapped overnight.  </></>Does that help?  Happy dinner partying!</p>
    </div>

