  <li id="comment-361" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2004/08/slow-roasting/#comment-361"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2009-07-16T02:24:25-04:00">Thursday, July 16, 2009 at 2:24 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Anonymous, I love that you bought a cake stand for this!  So pretty.  And as for your flour question, this recipe is designed for all-purpose flour, but you can substitute cake flour, yes.  You&#39;ll need to use a different amount, though.  <a href="http://bakingbites.com/2007/05/subbing-all-purpose-flour-for-cake-flour/" rel="nofollow">Here</a>&#39;s a great explanation of the difference between the two flours and how much to use when you&#39;re substituting one for the other.</p>
    </div>

